/* KCNA content - Container Orchestration (28% of exam). Auto-generated. */
KCNA.register({"id": "orchestration", "name": "Container Orchestration", "weight": 28, "notes": [{"id": "orchestration-note-1", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container orchestration fundamentals and why it is needed", "title": "Why Container Orchestration Exists", "html": "<p>Containers are lightweight and portable, but running them at scale by hand is impractical. Orchestration automates deployment, scaling, and operations of containers across many machines.</p><ul><li><strong>The problem:</strong> manually starting containers, restarting crashes, load-balancing, rolling updates, and placement across nodes does not scale past a few hosts.</li><li><strong>Orchestrator responsibilities:</strong> scheduling (placing workloads on suitable nodes), <strong>self-healing</strong> (restarting/replacing failed containers), <strong>horizontal scaling</strong>, <strong>service discovery</strong> and load balancing, <strong>rolling updates/rollbacks</strong>, and <strong>config/secret management</strong>.</li><li><strong>Declarative model:</strong> you declare a <em>desired state</em>; the orchestrator runs a continuous <strong>reconciliation loop</strong> to make actual state match. Kubernetes uses controllers for this.</li><li><strong>Kubernetes</strong> is the CNCF graduated, de facto standard orchestrator (donated by Google, based on Borg). Alternatives: Docker Swarm, HashiCorp Nomad.</li><li><strong>Key benefit:</strong> abstracts away individual servers; you treat the cluster as a single pool of compute.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Know <strong>declarative vs imperative</strong>: declarative (desired state) is the Kubernetes-native approach.</li><li>Self-healing and reconciliation loops are recurring KCNA themes.</li><li>The smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes is the <strong>Pod</strong>, not the container.</li><li>Orchestration enables resilience, scalability, and efficient resource utilization without manual intervention.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-2", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "title": "Runtimes, CRI, OCI, containerd and runc", "html": "<p>Kubernetes does not run containers itself; it delegates to a container runtime through a standard interface.</p><ul><li><strong>CRI (Container Runtime Interface):</strong> the gRPC API the <code>kubelet</code> uses to talk to a runtime. It decouples Kubernetes from any specific runtime.</li><li><strong>High-level runtimes</strong> (CRI-compatible): <strong>containerd</strong> (CNCF graduated) and <strong>CRI-O</strong>. They pull images, manage container lifecycle, and call a low-level runtime.</li><li><strong>Low-level runtime:</strong> <strong>runc</strong> is the reference OCI runtime that actually creates the container using Linux <strong>namespaces</strong> and <strong>cgroups</strong>.</li><li><strong>OCI (Open Container Initiative):</strong> defines open standards for the <strong>image-spec</strong> (image format) and <strong>runtime-spec</strong> (how to run a container). Hosted under the Linux Foundation.</li><li><strong>Dockershim removed:</strong> as of Kubernetes <strong>v1.24</strong>, Docker is no longer a directly supported runtime. Docker-built images still run fine (they are OCI-compliant).</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Order of delegation: <code>kubelet</code> → CRI → containerd/CRI-O → runc → container.</li><li><strong>CRI = the interface; OCI = image and runtime standards.</strong> Don't confuse them.</li><li>Sandboxed runtimes for stronger isolation: <strong>gVisor</strong> and <strong>Kata Containers</strong>.</li><li>containerd is the most common production runtime today.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-3", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster networking and the CNI (pod-to-pod networking, kube-proxy, DNS)", "title": "Cluster Networking and the CNI", "html": "<p>Kubernetes networking is built on a flat model where every Pod gets its own IP and can reach every other Pod without NAT.</p><ul><li><strong>The Kubernetes network model rules:</strong> every Pod has a unique IP; Pods communicate across nodes <em>without NAT</em>; containers in a Pod share the same network namespace (same IP, talk via <code>localhost</code>).</li><li><strong>CNI (Container Network Interface):</strong> a CNCF spec/plugin standard the kubelet uses to attach Pods to the network. Kubernetes ships no built-in network; you install a CNI plugin.</li><li><strong>Common CNI plugins:</strong> <strong>Calico</strong>, <strong>Cilium</strong> (eBPF-based), Flannel, Weave Net. Some (Calico, Cilium) also enforce NetworkPolicies.</li><li><strong>kube-proxy:</strong> runs on each node and implements <code>Service</code> virtual IPs by programming <strong>iptables</strong> or <strong>IPVS</strong> rules, load-balancing traffic to backing Pods. Cilium can replace kube-proxy with eBPF.</li><li><strong>Cluster DNS (CoreDNS):</strong> provides service discovery; Services get DNS names like <code>my-svc.my-namespace.svc.cluster.local</code>.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Know <strong>CNI = pod networking</strong>, <strong>kube-proxy = Service routing</strong>, <strong>CoreDNS = DNS/discovery</strong>.</li><li>Pods are ephemeral and IPs change; that's why Services and DNS exist.</li><li>CoreDNS is the default, CNCF-graduated DNS server in Kubernetes.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-4", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "title": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "html": "<p>These resources expose workloads and control traffic. Pods are ephemeral, so stable access goes through abstractions.</p><ul><li><strong>Service:</strong> a stable virtual IP + DNS name fronting a set of Pods selected by labels. Provides discovery and L4 load balancing.</li><li><strong>Service types:</strong><ul><li><strong>ClusterIP</strong> (default) — internal-only IP.</li><li><strong>NodePort</strong> — exposes a port on every node.</li><li><strong>LoadBalancer</strong> — provisions an external cloud load balancer.</li><li><strong>ExternalName</strong> — maps to an external DNS name (CNAME), no proxying.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Ingress:</strong> L7 (HTTP/HTTPS) routing by host/path into Services, with TLS termination. Requires an <strong>Ingress Controller</strong> (e.g. NGINX, Traefik) to do the work; the <code>Ingress</code> object alone does nothing.</li><li><strong>Gateway API:</strong> the newer, more expressive successor to Ingress.</li><li><strong>NetworkPolicy:</strong> firewall rules at the Pod level controlling allowed ingress/egress by label, namespace, or IP block. <strong>Default is allow-all</strong> until a policy selects a Pod; then it becomes deny-by-default for that direction. Requires a CNI that enforces them (Calico, Cilium).</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Ingress = HTTP L7; Service = L4. Ingader needs a controller.</li><li>NetworkPolicies are additive (allow-only); there is no explicit deny rule.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-5", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service mesh concepts (Istio, Linkerd, sidecars, mTLS, traffic management)", "title": "Service Mesh Concepts", "html": "<p>A service mesh adds a dedicated infrastructure layer for service-to-service communication, moving networking concerns out of application code.</p><ul><li><strong>Sidecar pattern:</strong> a proxy container (often <strong>Envoy</strong>) is injected alongside each Pod and intercepts all inbound/outbound traffic transparently.</li><li><strong>Data plane vs control plane:</strong> the <em>data plane</em> is the set of sidecar proxies that carry traffic; the <em>control plane</em> configures and manages them.</li><li><strong>Core capabilities:</strong><ul><li><strong>mTLS</strong> — automatic mutual TLS encryption and identity between services (zero-trust).</li><li><strong>Traffic management</strong> — canary releases, A/B routing, traffic splitting, retries, timeouts, circuit breaking.</li><li><strong>Observability</strong> — metrics, distributed tracing, and access logs out of the box.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Istio:</strong> feature-rich, uses Envoy sidecars (also offers ambient/sidecar-less mode). <strong>Linkerd:</strong> CNCF graduated, lightweight, simpler, uses its own Rust micro-proxy.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Know <strong>sidecar = data plane proxy</strong>; <strong>mTLS</strong> is a headline mesh benefit.</li><li>The mesh provides security, traffic control, and observability <em>without changing app code</em>.</li><li>Linkerd is the CNCF graduated mesh; Istio also graduated.</li><li>Trade-off: meshes add latency and operational complexity.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-6", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage orchestration and the CSI (StorageClasses, dynamic provisioning, access modes, reclaim policies)", "title": "Storage Orchestration and the CSI", "html": "<p>Kubernetes abstracts persistent storage so Pods can request durable volumes without knowing the backend.</p><ul><li><strong>CSI (Container Storage Interface):</strong> the standard plugin API for exposing storage systems (block/file) to Kubernetes; replaced legacy in-tree drivers.</li><li><strong>PersistentVolume (PV):</strong> a cluster storage resource (admin/provisioner side). <strong>PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC):</strong> a user's request for storage that binds to a PV.</li><li><strong>StorageClass:</strong> defines a <em>provisioner</em> and parameters; enables <strong>dynamic provisioning</strong> so a PV is created automatically when a PVC is made (no pre-provisioning).</li><li><strong>Access modes:</strong><ul><li><strong>ReadWriteOnce (RWO)</strong> — one node read/write.</li><li><strong>ReadOnlyMany (ROX)</strong> — many nodes read-only.</li><li><strong>ReadWriteMany (RWX)</strong> — many nodes read/write.</li><li><strong>ReadWriteOncePod (RWOP)</strong> — a single Pod.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Reclaim policies:</strong> <strong>Delete</strong> (PV and backing storage removed when PVC is deleted — common for dynamic) vs <strong>Retain</strong> (kept for manual handling). <em>Recycle</em> is deprecated.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Flow: <strong>StorageClass → PVC → dynamically provisioned PV → mounted in Pod</strong>.</li><li>RWO is per-node, not per-Pod; RWOP is per-Pod.</li><li>CSI lets vendors ship drivers out-of-tree, decoupled from Kubernetes releases.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-7", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Authorization with RBAC, Roles, RoleBindings and ServiceAccounts", "title": "RBAC, Roles, Bindings and ServiceAccounts", "html": "<p>RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) is the default authorization mode controlling who can do what on which Kubernetes resources.</p><ul><li><strong>Roles define permissions</strong> (verbs like <code>get</code>, <code>list</code>, <code>create</code>, <code>delete</code> on resources). They are purely additive — <strong>no deny rules</strong>; everything is denied unless explicitly allowed.</li><li><strong>Role vs ClusterRole:</strong><ul><li><code>Role</code> — namespaced permissions.</li><li><code>ClusterRole</code> — cluster-wide permissions (or reusable across namespaces; also covers cluster-scoped resources like nodes).</li></ul></li><li><strong>Bindings grant the role to a subject:</strong><ul><li><code>RoleBinding</code> — grants within a namespace.</li><li><code>ClusterRoleBinding</code> — grants cluster-wide.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Subjects:</strong> Users, Groups, and <strong>ServiceAccounts</strong>.</li><li><strong>ServiceAccount:</strong> an identity for <em>processes/Pods</em> (not humans) to authenticate to the API server. Each namespace has a <code>default</code> ServiceAccount; tokens are mounted into Pods.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Pattern: <strong>Role/ClusterRole (what) + Binding (who)</strong>.</li><li>A <code>RoleBinding</code> can reference a <code>ClusterRole</code> to reuse it within one namespace.</li><li>Users are external/not Kubernetes objects; ServiceAccounts are real API objects for workloads.</li><li>Follow <strong>least privilege</strong>; RBAC is allow-only.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "orchestration-note-8", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Security: the 4 Cs of cloud native security, securityContext, Pod Security Admission and supply-chain security", "title": "Cloud Native Security and the 4 Cs", "html": "<p>Cloud native security is layered; the outer layers must be secured before the inner ones matter.</p><ul><li><strong>The 4 Cs (outer → inner):</strong> <strong>Cloud</strong> (infrastructure/provider) → <strong>Cluster</strong> (API server, RBAC, network policies) → <strong>Container</strong> (image scanning, minimal images) → <strong>Code</strong> (app, dependencies, TLS). A weak outer layer undermines inner protections.</li><li><strong>securityContext:</strong> Pod/container settings that harden runtime, e.g. <code>runAsNonRoot</code>, <code>readOnlyRootFilesystem</code>, dropping Linux <strong>capabilities</strong>, <code>allowPrivilegeEscalation: false</code>, and disallowing <code>privileged</code> containers.</li><li><strong>Pod Security Admission (PSA):</strong> the built-in admission controller (replaced deprecated PodSecurityPolicy) that enforces the <strong>Pod Security Standards</strong> — <strong>Privileged</strong>, <strong>Baseline</strong>, <strong>Restricted</strong> — per namespace in modes <code>enforce</code>, <code>audit</code>, or <code>warn</code>.</li><li><strong>Supply-chain security:</strong> image signing/verification (<strong>Sigstore/cosign</strong>), <strong>SBOMs</strong> (software bill of materials), vulnerability scanning, and provenance (SLSA). <strong>Admission control</strong> (e.g. OPA/Gatekeeper, Kyverno) enforces policy on what may run.</li></ul><h4>Exam tips</h4><ul><li>Memorize 4 Cs order: <strong>Cloud, Cluster, Container, Code</strong>.</li><li>PSP is deprecated/removed → use <strong>Pod Security Admission</strong>.</li><li>Restricted is the most hardened Pod Security Standard.</li><li>Apply <strong>least privilege</strong> and avoid running as root.</li></ul>"}], "flashcards": [{"id": "orchestration-fc-1", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container orchestration fundamentals and why it is needed", "front": "What is container orchestration and why is it needed?", "back": "Container orchestration automates the deployment, scaling, networking, and lifecycle management of containers across a cluster of machines. It is needed because manually managing many containers across many hosts (scheduling, health, scaling, failover, networking) is impractical at scale."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-2", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container orchestration fundamentals and why it is needed", "front": "What is the desired-state (declarative) model in Kubernetes?", "back": "You declare the desired state of your workloads (e.g., 3 replicas) in manifests, and Kubernetes controllers continuously reconcile actual state toward that desired state, self-healing when reality drifts (e.g., restarting failed pods)."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-3", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container orchestration fundamentals and why it is needed", "front": "Name four core capabilities a container orchestrator provides.", "back": "Scheduling (placing containers on suitable nodes), self-healing (restarting/rescheduling failed containers), horizontal scaling, and service discovery/load balancing. It also handles rolling updates and rollbacks."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-4", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container orchestration fundamentals and why it is needed", "front": "What is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes, and what does it contain?", "back": "The Pod is the smallest deployable unit. It contains one or more tightly-coupled containers that share a network namespace (same IP and port space) and can share storage volumes."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-5", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "front": "What is the Container Runtime Interface (CRI)?", "back": "The CRI is a gRPC API/plugin interface that lets the kubelet talk to any compliant container runtime. It decouples Kubernetes from a specific runtime, so runtimes like containerd or CRI-O can be swapped in."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-6", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "front": "What is the difference between a high-level and a low-level container runtime?", "back": "A high-level runtime (e.g., containerd, CRI-O) manages images, the CRI, and container lifecycle, then delegates actual container creation to a low-level runtime (e.g., runc) that interacts with the kernel to start the process."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-7", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "front": "What does the OCI (Open Container Initiative) define?", "back": "The OCI defines open standards for container formats: the Runtime Spec (how to run a container), the Image Spec (image format), and the Distribution Spec (how images are distributed via registries)."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-8", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "front": "What is runc?", "back": "runc is the reference OCI-compliant low-level runtime. It is the CLI tool that actually creates and runs containers by setting up Linux namespaces and cgroups, and is used under the hood by containerd and CRI-O."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-9", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container runtimes, the CRI, containerd, CRI-O, runc and the OCI", "front": "Why was the Docker shim (dockershim) removed from Kubernetes?", "back": "Docker is not CRI-compliant, so the kubelet needed a special dockershim adapter. It was removed in Kubernetes 1.24 to reduce maintenance burden; clusters now use CRI runtimes like containerd or CRI-O directly."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-10", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster networking and the CNI (pod-to-pod networking, kube-proxy, DNS)", "front": "What are the fundamental rules of the Kubernetes network model?", "back": "Every Pod gets its own unique IP, all Pods can communicate with all other Pods across nodes without NAT, and agents on a node can reach all Pods on that node. This 'flat' network is implemented by a CNI plugin."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-11", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster networking and the CNI (pod-to-pod networking, kube-proxy, DNS)", "front": "What is the Container Network Interface (CNI)?", "back": "The CNI is a standard specification and set of plugins that configure network connectivity for Pods. Kubernetes uses a CNI plugin (e.g., Calico, Cilium, Flannel) to assign IPs and wire up pod-to-pod networking."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-12", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster networking and the CNI (pod-to-pod networking, kube-proxy, DNS)", "front": "What does kube-proxy do?", "back": "kube-proxy runs on each node and implements Service networking by maintaining network rules (using iptables or IPVS) that load-balance traffic destined for a Service's virtual IP to the backing Pod endpoints."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-13", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster networking and the CNI (pod-to-pod networking, kube-proxy, DNS)", "front": "What provides in-cluster DNS in Kubernetes, and how are Services resolved?", "back": "CoreDNS is the default cluster DNS. Services get a DNS name of the form <service>.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local, letting Pods discover and reach Services by name instead of IP."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-14", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "front": "List the main Kubernetes Service types and what each does.", "back": "ClusterIP: internal-only virtual IP (default). NodePort: exposes the Service on a static port on every node. LoadBalancer: provisions an external cloud load balancer. ExternalName: maps the Service to an external DNS name via a CNAME."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-15", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "front": "What is an Ingress, and what is required for it to work?", "back": "An Ingress is an API object that defines HTTP/HTTPS routing rules (host/path-based) to Services. It only takes effect when an Ingress Controller (e.g., NGINX, Traefik) is installed to fulfill those rules."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-16", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "front": "What does a NetworkPolicy do, and what is the default Pod connectivity?", "back": "A NetworkPolicy controls allowed ingress/egress traffic to Pods based on labels, namespaces, and ports. By default all Pods are non-isolated (allow all traffic); a NetworkPolicy selecting a Pod switches it to deny-by-default for that direction. It requires a CNI plugin that supports policies."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-17", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services, Ingress and NetworkPolicies", "front": "How does a Service know which Pods to send traffic to?", "back": "A Service uses a label selector to match Pods. Matching Pod IPs are tracked as Endpoints/EndpointSlices, and traffic is load-balanced across those endpoints."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-18", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service mesh concepts (Istio, Linkerd, sidecars, mTLS, traffic management)", "front": "What is a service mesh?", "back": "A service mesh is a dedicated infrastructure layer that manages service-to-service communication, providing traffic management, observability, and security (like mTLS) transparently, without changing application code."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-19", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service mesh concepts (Istio, Linkerd, sidecars, mTLS, traffic management)", "front": "What is the sidecar pattern in a service mesh?", "back": "A proxy container (e.g., Envoy in Istio) is injected alongside each application container in the Pod. It intercepts all inbound/outbound traffic, enforcing mesh policies and collecting metrics without app changes."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-20", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service mesh concepts (Istio, Linkerd, sidecars, mTLS, traffic management)", "front": "What is the data plane vs. control plane in a service mesh?", "back": "The data plane is the set of sidecar proxies that actually route and secure traffic between services. The control plane (e.g., Istiod) configures and manages those proxies and distributes policy and certificates."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-21", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service mesh concepts (Istio, Linkerd, sidecars, mTLS, traffic management)", "front": "What is mTLS in a service mesh, and what does it provide?", "back": "Mutual TLS authenticates both client and server and encrypts traffic between services. The mesh automates certificate issuance and rotation, providing encryption in transit and service identity without app changes."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-22", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage orchestration and the CSI (StorageClasses, dynamic provisioning, access modes, reclaim policies)", "front": "What is the Container Storage Interface (CSI)?", "back": "The CSI is a standard interface that lets storage vendors write plugins (drivers) to expose their storage systems to Kubernetes, decoupling storage support from the core Kubernetes codebase (out-of-tree)."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-23", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage orchestration and the CSI (StorageClasses, dynamic provisioning, access modes, reclaim policies)", "front": "What is the relationship between a PV, a PVC, and a StorageClass?", "back": "A PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) is a user's request for storage. A PersistentVolume (PV) is the actual storage resource. A StorageClass defines a 'class' of storage and enables dynamic provisioning, automatically creating a PV to satisfy a PVC."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-24", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage orchestration and the CSI (StorageClasses, dynamic provisioning, access modes, reclaim policies)", "front": "What is dynamic provisioning?", "back": "Dynamic provisioning automatically creates a PersistentVolume on demand when a PVC requests a StorageClass, instead of an admin pre-provisioning PVs manually. The StorageClass's provisioner handles creating the underlying storage."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-25", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage orchestration and the CSI (StorageClasses, dynamic provisioning, access modes, reclaim policies)", "front": "What are the PersistentVolume access modes and reclaim policies?", "back": "Access modes: ReadWriteOnce (RWO, one node), ReadOnlyMany (ROX), ReadWriteMany (RWX, many nodes), ReadWriteOncePod (one Pod). Reclaim policies on PV release: Retain (keep data), Delete (delete the volume), and the deprecated Recycle."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-26", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Authorization with RBAC, Roles, RoleBindings and ServiceAccounts", "front": "What is RBAC in Kubernetes?", "back": "Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) authorizes actions on API resources based on roles. It grants permissions (verbs like get/list/create on resources) to subjects (users, groups, ServiceAccounts) and is additive (no deny rules; default is deny)."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-27", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Authorization with RBAC, Roles, RoleBindings and ServiceAccounts", "front": "What is the difference between a Role and a ClusterRole (and their bindings)?", "back": "A Role grants permissions within a single namespace; a ClusterRole is cluster-scoped (or for cluster-wide resources like nodes). A RoleBinding grants a Role (or ClusterRole) within one namespace; a ClusterRoleBinding grants a ClusterRole cluster-wide."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-28", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Authorization with RBAC, Roles, RoleBindings and ServiceAccounts", "front": "What is a ServiceAccount, and how do Pods use it?", "back": "A ServiceAccount provides an identity for processes running in Pods to authenticate to the Kubernetes API. Each Pod uses the namespace's 'default' ServiceAccount unless one is specified, and its token can be mounted into the Pod."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-29", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Security: the 4 Cs of cloud native security, securityContext, Pod Security Admission and supply-chain security", "front": "What are the 4 Cs of Cloud Native Security?", "back": "Cloud, Cluster, Container, and Code. They form nested layers of defense-in-depth: each layer builds on the security of the layer surrounding it, and securing an outer layer is required to secure the inner ones."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-30", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Security: the 4 Cs of cloud native security, securityContext, Pod Security Admission and supply-chain security", "front": "What does Pod Security Admission (PSA) enforce, and what are its three levels and modes?", "back": "PSA is the built-in admission controller (replacing PodSecurityPolicy) that enforces the Pod Security Standards at the namespace level. Levels: Privileged, Baseline, Restricted. Modes: enforce, audit, warn."}, {"id": "orchestration-fc-31", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Security: the 4 Cs of cloud native security, securityContext, Pod Security Admission and supply-chain security", "front": "What is a securityContext, and name two key settings it controls.", "back": "A securityContext defines privilege and access control settings for a Pod or container. Key settings include runAsNonRoot, runAsUser, readOnlyRootFilesystem, allowPrivilegeEscalation, privileged, and dropping Linux capabilities."}], "questions": [{"id": "orchestration-q-1", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Orchestration fundamentals", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a container orchestrator like Kubernetes?", "options": ["To build container images from a Dockerfile and push them to a registry", "To automate the deployment, scaling, networking, and management of containerized workloads across a cluster of machines", "To replace the container runtime so containers no longer need an OS kernel", "To serve as a version control system for application source code"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A container orchestrator automates deploying, scaling, networking, and managing containers across many hosts. Building images (option A) is the job of tools like Docker/BuildKit, and orchestrators still rely on a container runtime and the host kernel, so they do not replace it."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-2", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Why orchestration is needed", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which problem becomes significantly harder to solve manually as the number of containers and hosts grows, making orchestration valuable?", "options": ["Writing the application's business logic", "Compiling source code into a binary", "Scheduling containers onto available nodes and keeping the desired number running", "Choosing a programming language for the application"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "As scale grows, manually placing containers on nodes and ensuring the right number stay running becomes error-prone and impractical; orchestrators automate scheduling and maintain desired state. The other options are development concerns unrelated to running containers at scale."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-3", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Desired state and self-healing", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A studier claims that container orchestration provides \"self-healing.\" Which behavior best illustrates this capability?", "options": ["The orchestrator patches security vulnerabilities inside the container image automatically", "The orchestrator automatically restarts or reschedules containers that fail or land on a failed node to restore the declared desired state", "The orchestrator rewrites application code to fix runtime bugs", "The orchestrator prevents any container from ever crashing"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Self-healing means the orchestrator continuously reconciles actual state with desired state, restarting failed containers and rescheduling them off failed nodes. It does not patch images, fix application code, or guarantee containers never crash."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-4", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Declarative vs imperative", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Kubernetes is described as following a declarative model. What does this mean in practice?", "options": ["You specify the exact sequence of commands to start each container in order", "You declare the desired end state, and the system continuously works to make the actual state match it", "You must manually approve every change before it is applied to the cluster", "You write imperative scripts that the scheduler executes once and then discards"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "In a declarative model you describe the desired state (e.g., \"run 3 replicas\") and controllers reconcile actual state toward it continuously. Specifying step-by-step commands (option A) describes an imperative approach, which Kubernetes de-emphasizes."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-5", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Orchestration value: scaling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which of the following is a benefit that container orchestration platforms provide for running applications at scale?", "options": ["Eliminating the need for any networking between services", "Automated horizontal scaling of workloads up or down based on demand or defined rules", "Guaranteeing zero cloud infrastructure cost", "Removing the need to monitor applications entirely"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Orchestrators support automated horizontal scaling (e.g., adding or removing replicas) in response to load or policy. They do not remove networking, eliminate costs, or remove the need for monitoring."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-6", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Orchestration vs container runtime", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "How does the role of a container orchestrator differ from that of a container runtime such as containerd?", "options": ["The orchestrator runs individual containers on a single host, while the runtime manages scheduling across the whole cluster", "They are identical; \"orchestrator\" and \"runtime\" are two names for the same component", "The runtime starts and runs containers on a node, while the orchestrator decides where containers should run and manages them across the cluster", "The orchestrator builds container images, while the runtime stores them in a registry"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A container runtime (e.g., containerd) is responsible for actually pulling images and starting/stopping containers on a node, while the orchestrator coordinates scheduling, scaling, and lifecycle across the cluster and delegates the low-level run to the runtime. They are distinct, complementary components."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-7", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Reconciliation and control loops", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "An operator deletes a Pod that is managed by a Deployment with 3 desired replicas. Why does a replacement Pod appear shortly afterward?", "options": ["The orchestrator caches the old Pod and re-displays it without actually running anything", "A controller's reconciliation loop detects that actual state (2 Pods) differs from desired state (3) and creates a new Pod to converge them", "The container runtime independently decides to clone the deleted Pod on its own", "Kubernetes blocks the deletion, so the Pod was never actually removed"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Controllers run continuous reconciliation (control) loops that compare actual state to declared desired state and act to close the gap. The Deployment's ReplicaSet controller sees only 2 of the 3 desired Pods and creates a replacement. The runtime does not make replica decisions, and the original deletion does in fact succeed."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-8", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container Runtimes & CRI", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What does the acronym CRI stand for in the context of Kubernetes?", "options": ["Container Runtime Interface", "Cloud Resource Initiative", "Cluster Runtime Integration", "Container Registry Index"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "CRI stands for Container Runtime Interface, the gRPC-based API that lets the kubelet talk to container runtimes without being tied to a specific implementation. The other expansions are not real Kubernetes terms."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-9", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container Runtimes & CRI", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes node component communicates with the container runtime through the CRI?", "options": ["kube-proxy", "kube-scheduler", "kubelet", "kube-controller-manager"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "The kubelet runs on each node and uses the CRI (a gRPC interface) to instruct the container runtime to pull images and manage pods and containers. kube-proxy handles service networking, while the scheduler and controller-manager run on the control plane and do not talk to runtimes."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-10", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "OCI Specifications", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "The Open Container Initiative (OCI) primarily maintains specifications in which areas?", "options": ["Image format, runtime behavior, and image distribution", "Pod scheduling and node autoscaling", "Service discovery and load balancing", "Cluster authentication and RBAC policy"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The OCI maintains three specifications: the Image Spec (how container images are packaged), the Runtime Spec (how to run a filesystem bundle), and the Distribution Spec (how images are pushed/pulled). Scheduling, networking, and RBAC are Kubernetes concerns, not OCI."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-11", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Low-level Runtimes", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the role of runc in the container runtime stack?", "options": ["It is a high-level runtime that implements the CRI for the kubelet", "It is a low-level (OCI) runtime that actually creates and runs the container process", "It is a container registry for storing OCI images", "It is the kubelet plugin that configures pod networking"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "runc is the reference low-level OCI runtime: it uses Linux kernel features (namespaces, cgroups) to spawn and run the container process from an OCI bundle. High-level runtimes like containerd and CRI-O call runc to do this; runc itself does not implement the CRI."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-12", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "High-level Runtimes", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which option lists two high-level container runtimes that implement the Kubernetes CRI?", "options": ["containerd and CRI-O", "runc and crun", "Docker Engine and runc", "etcd and containerd"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "containerd and CRI-O are CRI-compliant high-level runtimes that the kubelet can use directly. runc and crun are low-level OCI runtimes (not CRI implementations), and etcd is the cluster datastore."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-13", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Runtime History", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Starting with Kubernetes v1.24, what changed regarding Docker as a container runtime?", "options": ["Docker images can no longer run on Kubernetes nodes", "The dockershim was removed, so the kubelet no longer talks to Docker directly; a CRI-compatible runtime is required", "Docker became the only supported CRI runtime", "Kubernetes began bundling Docker Engine with every node by default"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "In v1.24 the built-in dockershim adapter was removed, so the kubelet can no longer use Docker Engine directly; nodes must use a CRI runtime such as containerd or CRI-O. OCI/Docker-format images still run fine because they follow the OCI image spec."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-14", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Runtime Architecture", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "CRI-O was designed primarily to serve which purpose?", "options": ["A general-purpose runtime for desktop container development", "A lightweight CRI implementation purpose-built to run OCI-compliant containers for Kubernetes", "A replacement for etcd as the cluster state store", "A container image registry optimized for air-gapped clusters"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "CRI-O is a lightweight container runtime created specifically to implement the Kubernetes CRI and run OCI-compliant images, giving Kubernetes a minimal runtime without extra features it does not need. It is not a registry, a state store, or a desktop development tool."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-15", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes component is responsible for in-cluster DNS, allowing Pods to resolve Services by name (e.g., my-svc.my-namespace.svc.cluster.local)?", "options": ["kube-proxy", "CoreDNS", "etcd", "kubelet"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "CoreDNS is the default cluster DNS server in modern Kubernetes, providing name resolution for Services and Pods. kube-proxy handles Service traffic routing but does not resolve names, etcd is the cluster datastore, and the kubelet manages Pods on a node."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-16", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Under the standard Kubernetes networking model, how can two Pods on different nodes communicate by default?", "options": ["Directly using each other's Pod IP addresses without NAT", "Only through a NodePort Service that exposes the destination Pod", "Only after manually configuring iptables NAT rules on each node", "Through the kubelet, which proxies all inter-Pod traffic"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The Kubernetes network model requires that every Pod gets its own IP and that all Pods can reach each other across nodes without NAT. A CNI plugin implements this flat network; NodePort Services and manual NAT are not required for basic Pod-to-Pod traffic, and the kubelet does not proxy inter-Pod traffic."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-17", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the primary purpose of the Container Network Interface (CNI) in a Kubernetes cluster?", "options": ["To schedule Pods onto nodes based on resource requests", "To store the cluster's network configuration in etcd", "To provide a standard plugin interface for configuring Pod network connectivity and IP assignment", "To load-balance external traffic into the cluster via an Ingress controller"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "CNI is a CNCF specification with a set of plugins (e.g., Calico, Cilium, Flannel) that the kubelet invokes to set up Pod networking, including connecting Pods to the network and assigning IP addresses. Scheduling, etcd storage, and Ingress are handled by other components."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-18", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A ClusterIP Service has been created, but the virtual ClusterIP is not a real network interface anywhere. Which component programs the node-level rules (e.g., iptables or IPVS) that redirect traffic sent to the ClusterIP toward the backing Pods?", "options": ["CoreDNS", "kube-proxy", "The container runtime", "The Ingress controller"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "kube-proxy watches Services and EndpointSlices and programs each node's iptables or IPVS rules so that traffic to a Service's virtual ClusterIP is forwarded to a healthy backing Pod. CoreDNS only resolves the Service name to that ClusterIP."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-19", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "By default, how does kube-proxy distribute connections among the multiple Pods backing a single ClusterIP Service?", "options": ["It always sends traffic to the Pod with the lowest CPU usage", "It load-balances connections across the available backend Pods", "It sends all traffic to the first Pod listed in the EndpointSlice", "It requires an external load balancer to choose a backend Pod"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "kube-proxy spreads connections across the Service's healthy backend Pods (for example, probabilistically with iptables mode or round-robin with IPVS mode). It does not pin traffic to a single Pod, and no external load balancer is needed for ClusterIP."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-20", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Which Kubernetes resource is used to control which Pods are allowed to communicate with each other at the IP/port level, and what is required for it to actually take effect?", "options": ["A Service of type ClusterIP, which is enforced automatically by kube-proxy", "A NetworkPolicy, which is only enforced if the cluster's CNI plugin supports it", "An Ingress resource, which is enforced by CoreDNS", "A ResourceQuota, which the kubelet enforces per node"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "NetworkPolicy objects define allowed ingress/egress traffic between Pods, but the Kubernetes API does not enforce them itself; a NetworkPolicy-capable CNI plugin (such as Calico or Cilium) must be installed. Without such a plugin, NetworkPolicy objects are accepted but have no effect."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-21", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cluster Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Pod looks up a Service using only its short name, such as 'web', and resolution succeeds even though the full name is web.default.svc.cluster.local. What mechanism makes the short name resolvable?", "options": ["kube-proxy rewrites the DNS query to add the namespace", "The Pod's /etc/resolv.conf includes search domains that the resolver appends so CoreDNS can complete the name", "CoreDNS broadcasts all Service names to every Pod at startup", "The container runtime maintains a local hosts file with every Service name"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kubelet configures each Pod's /etc/resolv.conf with the cluster DNS server and search domains (like default.svc.cluster.local, svc.cluster.local, and cluster.local), so the resolver appends these suffixes and CoreDNS resolves the short name. kube-proxy is not involved in DNS resolution."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-22", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Service type exposes an application only on a cluster-internal IP address, making it reachable from other Pods inside the cluster but not from outside?", "options": ["NodePort", "LoadBalancer", "ClusterIP", "ExternalName"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "ClusterIP is the default Service type and exposes the Service on an internal virtual IP reachable only within the cluster. NodePort and LoadBalancer build on top of ClusterIP to add external access, and ExternalName maps the Service to an external DNS name rather than providing a cluster-internal IP for Pods."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-23", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "How does a Service know which Pods to send traffic to?", "options": ["By matching the Pods' labels to the Service's label selector", "By referencing each Pod's name explicitly in the Service spec", "By matching the namespace of the Pods to the Service's namespace only", "By using the Pods' IP addresses hard-coded in the Service definition"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Service selects backend Pods using a label selector; Pods whose labels match are added to the Service's set of endpoints (tracked via EndpointSlices). Pods are not referenced by name or hard-coded IP, since Pod IPs are ephemeral and the set of matching Pods changes dynamically."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-24", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the primary purpose of an Ingress resource in Kubernetes?", "options": ["To assign a static external IP to every Pod in the cluster", "To manage external HTTP and HTTPS access to Services, typically with host- and path-based routing", "To enforce which Pods are allowed to communicate with each other", "To automatically scale the number of Pod replicas based on traffic"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "An Ingress manages external HTTP/HTTPS access to in-cluster Services and supports routing rules based on host name and URL path, plus optional TLS termination. Controlling Pod-to-Pod communication is the job of NetworkPolicies, and scaling replicas is handled by the HorizontalPodAutoscaler."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-25", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "An Ingress resource has been created, but external requests to the defined hosts are not being routed. What is the most likely missing component?", "options": ["A CoreDNS deployment", "An Ingress controller running in the cluster", "A second LoadBalancer Service", "An additional ClusterIP for each backend"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "An Ingress resource only defines routing rules; it does nothing on its own. An Ingress controller (such as ingress-nginx, Traefik, or Contour) must be deployed to actually read those rules and route traffic. CoreDNS handles in-cluster DNS, not Ingress routing."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-26", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What does a Kubernetes NetworkPolicy primarily control?", "options": ["The CPU and memory limits available to Pods", "Which Pods or endpoints are allowed to communicate with each other at the network level", "How DNS names are resolved inside the cluster", "The order in which Pods are scheduled onto nodes"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A NetworkPolicy defines rules governing allowed ingress and egress network traffic to and from selected Pods, acting like a firewall at the Pod level. Note that enforcement requires a CNI plugin that supports NetworkPolicy. Resource limits, DNS resolution, and scheduling are governed by other Kubernetes mechanisms."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-27", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In a cluster using a CNI plugin that supports NetworkPolicy, no NetworkPolicies have been applied to any Pod. What is the default behavior for traffic between Pods?", "options": ["All Pod-to-Pod traffic is denied until a policy explicitly allows it", "All Pods can communicate freely with one another", "Only Pods within the same namespace can communicate", "All egress is allowed but all ingress is denied by default"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "By default, Kubernetes is non-isolating: with no NetworkPolicy selecting them, all Pods accept traffic from any source and may send traffic anywhere. A Pod becomes isolated only once it is selected by at least one policy, after which only explicitly allowed traffic is permitted for the relevant direction(s)."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-28", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A NetworkPolicy is created that selects a set of Pods and specifies only an 'ingress' rule allowing traffic from one specific application. What happens to other ingress traffic and to egress traffic from those Pods?", "options": ["Other ingress traffic is denied, and all egress traffic remains allowed", "Both other ingress and all egress traffic are denied", "Other ingress traffic is allowed, but all egress traffic is denied", "Both ingress and egress traffic remain fully allowed since policies are additive"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Defining an ingress rule causes 'Ingress' to be included in policyTypes, so the selected Pods become isolated for ingress and any ingress traffic not explicitly allowed is denied. Egress is only restricted if the policy includes an egress section (or lists 'Egress' in policyTypes); since this policy defines only ingress, egress remains unaffected and allowed."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-29", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In a service mesh like Istio or Linkerd, what is the primary role of the \"sidecar\" proxy?", "options": ["It runs as a separate container alongside the application container in the same Pod to intercept and manage that Pod's network traffic", "It runs as a single cluster-wide Deployment that proxies traffic for every Pod in the cluster", "It replaces the application container entirely and runs the business logic itself", "It runs only on the control-plane nodes to schedule application Pods"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A sidecar proxy is deployed as an additional container in the same Pod as the application, transparently intercepting inbound and outbound traffic for that workload. It is not a single cluster-wide proxy, and it never replaces the application container."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-30", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which capability is a service mesh primarily designed to provide?", "options": ["Persistent block storage for stateful applications", "Container image building and registry hosting", "Service-to-service communication features such as observability, traffic management, and security (mTLS)", "Cluster node provisioning and operating-system patching"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A service mesh manages communication between services, adding observability, traffic control, and security like mutual TLS. Storage, image building, and node provisioning are unrelated concerns handled by other tools."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-31", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A service mesh is commonly described as having two parts. What is the role of the data plane?", "options": ["It stores the cluster's configuration in etcd", "It consists of the proxies that actually carry and handle the service traffic based on configuration from the control plane", "It is the component that configures policy and pushes rules to the proxies", "It schedules Pods onto worker nodes"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The data plane is made up of the proxies (sidecars or per-node proxies) that handle the actual request traffic, while the control plane configures and manages those proxies. Pushing configuration and policy is the control plane's job, not the data plane's."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-32", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What does mutual TLS (mTLS), as provided by a service mesh, add compared to standard (one-way) TLS?", "options": ["It encrypts traffic but does not authenticate either endpoint", "Only the client verifies the server's identity, exactly like a typical web browser connection", "Both the client and the server present and verify certificates, so each side authenticates the other", "It removes the need for encryption by relying solely on network firewalls"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "With mTLS both endpoints present certificates and verify each other, giving two-way authentication in addition to encryption. Standard one-way TLS only has the client verify the server's identity."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-33", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A team wants to gradually shift a small percentage of live traffic to a new version of a service to validate it before full rollout. Which service mesh capability best supports this?", "options": ["Traffic management with weighted traffic splitting between service versions", "Horizontal Pod autoscaling based on CPU usage", "Mutual TLS certificate rotation", "Persistent volume claims for the new version"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Service meshes support traffic management, including percentage-based (weighted) routing that enables canary releases and A/B testing. Autoscaling, certificate rotation, and storage do not control how request traffic is split between versions."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-34", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A key architectural difference between Linkerd and Istio is the choice of data-plane proxy. Which statement is accurate?", "options": ["Linkerd uses its own purpose-built, lightweight Rust-based micro-proxy, while Istio's default sidecar data plane uses the Envoy proxy", "Both Linkerd and Istio use the Envoy proxy as their data plane by default", "Linkerd uses Envoy while Istio uses a custom Rust proxy", "Neither project uses any kind of proxy; both rely entirely on application code changes"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Linkerd ships its own lightweight Rust-based micro-proxy (linkerd2-proxy), whereas Istio's data plane is built on Envoy (used by the default sidecar mode and as the waypoint proxy in ambient mode). This is a frequently cited distinction between the two CNCF meshes."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-35", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Service Mesh", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Which statement best describes why a service mesh can provide features like retries, mTLS, and telemetry without changing application source code?", "options": ["The mesh recompiles the application binary at deploy time to inject the features", "Sidecar proxies transparently intercept the Pod's network traffic, so these features are applied at the proxy layer rather than in application code", "The features are added by modifying the container image's base operating system kernel", "Kubernetes automatically rewrites application code through admission webhooks"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Because sidecar proxies sit in the network path and transparently intercept traffic, the mesh can apply retries, encryption, and telemetry at the proxy layer without touching application code. The mesh does not recompile binaries or rewrite application source."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-36", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Storage Orchestration", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In Kubernetes, what is the primary purpose of a StorageClass?", "options": ["To define how a volume is dynamically provisioned, including which provisioner and parameters to use", "To grant a Pod permission to mount a specific PersistentVolume", "To set the maximum amount of CPU and memory a volume may consume", "To encrypt all data written to a node's local disk by default"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A StorageClass describes a 'class' of storage and tells Kubernetes which provisioner and parameters to use when dynamically creating PersistentVolumes. It is not an access-control object (that is RBAC) and does not manage CPU/memory limits."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-37", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Dynamic Provisioning", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "A developer creates a PersistentVolumeClaim that references a StorageClass, and no matching PersistentVolume exists yet. What typically happens?", "options": ["The claim stays Pending forever because an administrator must manually create the volume first", "A new PersistentVolume is automatically provisioned to satisfy the claim", "The claim is rejected because PVCs cannot reference a StorageClass", "Kubernetes binds the claim to any existing volume regardless of size or class"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "When a PVC references a StorageClass, the associated provisioner dynamically creates a matching PersistentVolume automatically, removing the need for an admin to pre-provision storage. Manual creation describes static provisioning, the opposite approach."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-38", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Container Storage Interface", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What problem does the Container Storage Interface (CSI) primarily solve in the cloud native ecosystem?", "options": ["It compresses container images to reduce registry storage costs", "It provides a standard API so storage vendors can write a single plugin that works across container orchestrators without modifying Kubernetes core code", "It replaces etcd as the backing store for cluster state", "It defines a network protocol for replicating volumes between clusters"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "CSI is a standard interface that lets storage vendors develop drivers independently of the orchestrator's release cycle, instead of having storage code built into Kubernetes itself ('in-tree'). It is unrelated to image compression, etcd, or cross-cluster replication."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-39", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Access Modes", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A team needs a volume that can be mounted as read-write by multiple Pods on different nodes at the same time. Which access mode supports this?", "options": ["ReadWriteOnce (RWO)", "ReadOnlyMany (ROX)", "ReadWriteMany (RWX)", "ReadWriteOncePod (RWOP)"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "ReadWriteMany allows the volume to be mounted read-write by many nodes simultaneously. ReadWriteOnce limits read-write mounting to a single node, ReadOnlyMany permits many readers but no writers, and ReadWriteOncePod restricts access to a single Pod."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-40", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Reclaim Policies", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A PersistentVolume has its reclaim policy set to Delete. What happens to the underlying storage when the bound PersistentVolumeClaim is deleted?", "options": ["The PersistentVolume is retained and must be manually cleaned up by an administrator", "Both the PersistentVolume and the underlying storage asset are automatically removed", "The volume's data is wiped but the PersistentVolume object remains Available for reuse", "The claim deletion is blocked until the policy is changed to Retain"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "With a reclaim policy of Delete, removing the PVC causes Kubernetes to delete both the PersistentVolume object and the backing storage (for example, the cloud disk). The Retain policy is what keeps the volume for manual cleanup."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-41", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Reclaim Policies", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which reclaim policy keeps a PersistentVolume and its data intact after the bound PersistentVolumeClaim is deleted, requiring manual handling before reuse?", "options": ["Delete", "Recycle", "Retain", "Snapshot"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "The Retain reclaim policy preserves the PersistentVolume and its data after the PVC is deleted, leaving the volume in a Released state that an administrator must manually reclaim. Delete removes the volume, Recycle is deprecated, and Snapshot is not a reclaim policy."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-42", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Dynamic Provisioning", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In a cluster with a StorageClass marked as the default, a developer submits a PersistentVolumeClaim that omits the storageClassName field entirely. What is the expected behavior?", "options": ["The PVC is rejected because storageClassName is a required field", "The PVC uses the cluster's default StorageClass and is dynamically provisioned", "The PVC binds only to pre-existing PersistentVolumes that have no class", "The PVC remains Pending until the developer explicitly names a StorageClass"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "When a PVC omits storageClassName and a default StorageClass is configured (marked via the storageclass.kubernetes.io/is-default-class annotation), the DefaultStorageClass admission controller applies that default and the volume is provisioned dynamically. Omitting the field is not an error; binding only to class-less PVs requires setting storageClassName to an empty string."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-43", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes RBAC", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In Kubernetes RBAC, what is the primary purpose of a Role?", "options": ["To define a set of permissions (rules) for resources within a single namespace", "To grant a user cluster-wide administrative access", "To bind an identity to a set of permissions", "To create a network policy that controls pod-to-pod traffic"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Role contains rules that represent a set of permissions (verbs on resources) scoped to a single namespace. Binding an identity to those permissions is the job of a RoleBinding, not the Role itself, and cluster-wide permissions require a ClusterRole. Network traffic is controlled by NetworkPolicy, which is unrelated to RBAC."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-44", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes RBAC", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes object grants the permissions defined in a Role to a user, group, or ServiceAccount?", "options": ["RoleBinding", "ServiceAccount", "NetworkPolicy", "ResourceQuota"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A RoleBinding associates (binds) a Role with one or more subjects (users, groups, or ServiceAccounts), actually granting them the permissions. A ServiceAccount is only an identity and does not grant permissions by itself; NetworkPolicy governs pod traffic and ResourceQuota limits resource consumption."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-45", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes RBAC", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the key difference between a Role and a ClusterRole in Kubernetes RBAC?", "options": ["A Role is namespaced, while a ClusterRole is non-namespaced and can grant access to cluster-scoped resources", "A Role grants read-only access, while a ClusterRole grants read-write access", "A Role applies to ServiceAccounts, while a ClusterRole applies only to human users", "A Role is defined in YAML, while a ClusterRole is defined only via kubectl flags"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Role is scoped to a single namespace, whereas a ClusterRole is cluster-scoped and can grant permissions to cluster-scoped resources (like nodes) or to namespaced resources across all namespaces. The distinction is about scope, not read vs. write, subject type, or how the object is authored."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-46", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes Authorization", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A pod needs to call the Kubernetes API and authenticate as a specific identity. Which object provides this in-cluster identity for the pod?", "options": ["A ServiceAccount", "A RoleBinding", "A ConfigMap", "A ClusterRole"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A ServiceAccount provides an identity for processes running in pods to authenticate to the API server. ConfigMaps store configuration data and do not provide identity, while Roles, ClusterRoles, and bindings define and grant permissions rather than supply the identity itself."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-47", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes RBAC", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "If a pod is created without specifying a ServiceAccount, what identity does it use?", "options": ["The 'default' ServiceAccount in the pod's namespace", "The cluster-admin ServiceAccount", "No identity at all; the pod cannot reach the API server", "A randomly generated ServiceAccount created at pod startup"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Every namespace has a 'default' ServiceAccount, and pods that do not specify one are automatically assigned it. By default this account has minimal permissions, so it does not grant cluster-admin access. There is no auto-generated per-pod ServiceAccount."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-48", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes RBAC", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "You want to grant the same set of permissions to a ServiceAccount in many different namespaces using a single, reusable permission definition. Which approach is the most appropriate?", "options": ["Define one ClusterRole and create a separate RoleBinding (referencing that ClusterRole) in each namespace", "Define a separate Role in every namespace and bind each one individually", "Use a single ClusterRoleBinding referencing a Role", "Create one RoleBinding in the kube-system namespace that applies globally"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A common pattern is to define permissions once in a ClusterRole and then reference it from a RoleBinding in each namespace, which limits the granted access to that namespace while reusing the definition. A RoleBinding cannot reference a namespaced Role across namespaces, a ClusterRoleBinding can only reference a ClusterRole (not a Role) and would grant access cluster-wide, and a RoleBinding only applies within its own namespace."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-49", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Kubernetes Authorization", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "In a Role's rules, what do the 'verbs' (such as get, list, watch, create, delete) specify?", "options": ["The actions that are allowed to be performed on the specified resources", "The network protocols permitted between pods", "The lifecycle phases a pod passes through", "The order in which controllers reconcile objects"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "In RBAC, verbs define which actions (e.g., get, list, watch, create, update, delete) a subject may perform on the listed resources. RBAC is purely additive and allow-based, so verbs describe permitted operations and have nothing to do with networking or pod lifecycle."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-50", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cloud Native Security", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In the \"4 Cs of Cloud Native Security\" model, what are the four layers, ordered from the outermost to the innermost?", "options": ["Cloud, Cluster, Container, Code", "Code, Container, Cluster, Cloud", "Cloud, Cluster, Compute, Code", "Container, Cluster, Cloud, Code"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The 4 Cs are Cloud, Cluster, Container, and Code, layered from the outermost (Cloud) inward to the innermost (Code). Each inner layer relies on the security of the layers outside it, so weak Cloud security undermines everything inside."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-51", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Cloud Native Security", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "According to the 4 Cs defense-in-depth model, why does the order of the layers matter?", "options": ["Each layer is fully independent, so they can be secured in any order without consequence", "The innermost Code layer protects all the outer layers from attack", "Strong security at an inner layer cannot fully compensate for weak security at an outer layer, so the outer layers must also be secured", "Only the Cloud layer needs to be secured because it controls all the others"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "The 4 Cs build on each other as defense in depth: a secure inner layer cannot fully compensate for an insecure outer layer. Strong code security provides little protection if the surrounding Container, Cluster, or Cloud layers are weak."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-52", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Pod Security", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which field in a Pod or container specification is used to define privilege and access control settings such as running as a non-root user, dropping Linux capabilities, or setting a read-only root filesystem?", "options": ["resources", "securityContext", "imagePullPolicy", "serviceAccountName"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The securityContext field (available at both the Pod and container level) defines privilege and access control settings like runAsNonRoot, capabilities, and readOnlyRootFilesystem. The resources field sets CPU/memory requests and limits, imagePullPolicy controls when images are pulled, and serviceAccountName assigns an identity, none of which govern process privileges."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-53", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Pod Security", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the relationship between a securityContext set at the Pod level and one set at the container level within the same Pod?", "options": ["Pod-level settings always override container-level settings", "Container-level settings are ignored entirely when a Pod-level securityContext exists", "Container-level settings override Pod-level settings for that container when both specify the same field", "The two are merged by combining their values, never overriding"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A Pod-level securityContext applies as a default to all containers, but when a container specifies its own securityContext for the same field, the container-level value takes precedence for that container."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-54", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Pod Security Admission", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Pod Security Admission (PSA) enforces the Pod Security Standards. Which set of three standard levels does it use?", "options": ["Open, Restricted, Locked", "Privileged, Baseline, Restricted", "Low, Medium, High", "Permissive, Audit, Enforce"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The three Pod Security Standards levels are Privileged (unrestricted), Baseline (minimally restrictive, prevents known privilege escalations), and Restricted (heavily restricted, follows hardening best practices). Audit and enforce are PSA modes, not standard levels."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-55", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Pod Security Admission", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Pod Security Admission is applied at the namespace level using labels for three modes: enforce, audit, and warn. What does the \"enforce\" mode do when a Pod violates the configured Pod Security Standard?", "options": ["It allows the Pod but records a violation event in the audit log", "It allows the Pod but returns a user-facing warning to the client", "It rejects the Pod so it is not admitted to the namespace", "It admits the Pod but immediately evicts it after it starts running"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "In enforce mode, a policy violation causes the Pod to be rejected and not admitted. The audit mode only records violations in the audit log, and warn mode returns a warning to the user, but both of those still allow the Pod to be created."}, {"id": "orchestration-q-56", "domainId": "orchestration", "topic": "Supply-Chain Security", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "An organization wants to strengthen software supply-chain security for its container images. Which practice most directly helps ensure that a deployed image is exactly the trusted artifact that was built, and has not been tampered with?", "options": ["Cryptographically signing images and verifying those signatures before deployment", "Always using the \"latest\" tag so the newest image is pulled on every deploy", "Granting the cluster service account cluster-admin to simplify image pulls", "Disabling TLS on the registry to speed up image transfers"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Signing images (e.g., with tools like Sigstore/cosign) and verifying signatures before deployment establishes provenance and integrity, ensuring the artifact has not been tampered with. Using \"latest\" actually harms reproducibility, and the other options weaken security."}]});
